From: SeongJae Park <sj@kernel.org>
Date: Fri, 6 Mar 2026 17:07:53 -0800
Subject: [PATCH] ==== failed region charge rate ====

mm/damon: introduce DAMOS failed region quota charge ratio

Using DAMOS, users can request to memory of a specific access pattern
what system operation (DAMOS action) should be applied.  For example,
reclaiming memory that not accessed for two minutes or longer.  On
systems and workloads that have dynamic access pattern, changing the
action target access pattern accordingly in a timely manner is
challenging.  In the case, DAMOS could apply the action to too much
memory, impose unexpected overhead and result unexpected system status.

To avoid such unexpected aggressive behavior, DAMOS quota feature is
introduced.  It allows users to set the upper-limit memory amount that
the system operation action can be applied in a give time period.

DAMOS action is applied to all pages of memory region of the access
pattern,  For some of the pages, the action can fail.  For example,
pageout DAMOS action will fail for mlock()-ed pages in the region.
DAMOS quota is charged to all memory that the action was tried to be
applied, regardless of the successfulness of the attempt.  The charging
rule arguably makes DAMOS quota difficult to understand and finely
control.

Let's suppose entire system memory is cold, and the user runs
DAMOS-based proactive reclamation with a quota, say, 100 MiB per second.
The user may expect free memory will increase ~100 MiB per second.  But,
let's suppose about half of the memory is mlock()-ed.  A portion of the
quota will be charged by the mlock()-ed area, which cannot be reclaimed.
As a result, from the user's perspective, the reclamation progress looks
slow in general, and very unpredictable.  Sometiems it makes 100 MiB per
second progress, but sometimes be very slow.

The user can understand it is due to action-failed memory by monitoring
the DAMOS stat, because it shows the amount of memory that the action
application was successful and failed.  And, after all, the quota is
working as documented.  It is not a bug but a feature.

But, the behavior is not really useful.  First of all, monitoring DAMOS
stat is arguably additional burden for the users.  Also, the DAMOS
action progress depending on not only the quota, but also the access
pattern.  Users should suspect and investigate two things to understand
why the progress was not made.

Worse yet, the behavior is not really helpful for the initial intent:
aggressiveness.  The basic idea behine the current behavior was that,
even for action-failed memory, some of the overhead may be imposed, so
better to equally charge for memory regardless of the action
successfulness.  In the real world, however, the overhead for action
failed region is much smaller than that for successful region.  For the
above example, for mlock()-ed pages, DAMOS will just see it is
mlock()-ed and skip to next page.  Meanwhile, for action-successful
memory, it will also check if it is mlcok()-ed, and do the costly
pageout work.

So it still makes sense to charge some of the quota for the
action-failed memory.  But, charging it same as the action-success
memory is not fair.  Let users set the charge ratio for the
action-failed memory, by specifying the numerator and denominator of the
ratio.  For example, let's suppose the ratio is set to 1/4,096.  If the
DAMOS scheme action is applied to 5 GiB memory.  For 1 GiB of the
memory, the action is successed.  For the rest (4 GiB), the action is
failed.  Then, only 1 GiB and 1 MiB quota is charged.

The optimal charge ratio will depend on the use case and
system/workload.  I recommend to starting from 1/4,096, since must DAMOS
actions are applied in page granularity, and many systems have 4 KiB
page size.

Tests
=====

I tested this feature in below steps.

1. Allocate 50% of system memory and mlock() it using a test program.
2. Fill up page cache to exhaust nearly all free memory.
3. Start DAMON-based proactive reclamation with 100 MiB/second
   hard-quota.  Auto-tune the soft-quota under the hard-quota for
   achieving 40% free memory of the system with 'temporal' tuner.

For the step 1, I used a simple C program that written by Gemini.  It is
too simple, so I'm not sharing the code here.

For the step 2, I use dd command like below:

   dd if=/dev/zero of=foo bs=1M count=$50_percent_of_system_memory

For the step 3, I use the latest version of DAMON user-space tool (damo)
like below.

    sudo ./damo start --damos_action pageout \
            ` # Do the pageout only up to 100 MiB per second `
            --damos_quota_space 100M --damos_quota_interval 1s \
            ` # Auto-tune the quota below the hard quota aiming` \
            ` # 40% free memory of the node 0 ` \
            ` # (entire node of the test system)` \
            --damos_quota_goal node_mem_free_bp 40% 0 \
            ` # use temporal tuner, which is easy to understnd ` \
            --damos_quota_goal_tuner temporal

As expected, the progress of the reclamation is not consistent, because
the quota is exceeded for the failed reclamation of the unreclamable memory.

I do this again, but with failed region charge ratio feature.  For this,
the above 'damo' command is used, after appending below command line option.
Note that the option was added to 'damo' after v3.1.9.

    sudo ./damo start --damos_action pageout \
            [...]
            ` # quota-charge only 1/4096 for pageout-failed regions ` \
            --damos_quota_fail_charge_ratio 1 4096

As expected, the progress of the reclamation was nearly 100 MiB per
second until the goal is achieved.

